{{one source|date=June 2009}}
'''[[Re-education through labor]]''' ('''RTL'''; in Chinese, ''laodong jiaoyang'' 劳动教养, abbreviated '''''láojiào''''' 劳教) is a system of administrative detentions in the [[People's Republic of China]]. The estimated number of detainees in re-education through labor camps is anywhere from 300,000 (''[[China Labor Bulletin]]'', 2007)<ref name="AHRC">{{cite web | url=http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=8628&size=A | title=Human rights groups doubt 'laojiao' abolished | date=2 March 2007 | accessdate=18 October 2008 | work=[http://www.asianews.it/index.php?l=en&size=A AsiaNews]}}</ref> to 2 million (Laogai Research Foundation, 2006).<ref name="Laogai research">{{cite web | url=http://laogai.org/system/files/u1/handbook2008-all.pdf | title=Laogai Handbook (2007&ndash;2008) | publisher=The Laogai Research Foundation | year=2008 | accessdate=6 September 2010 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017235210/http://laogai.org/system/files/u1/handbook2008-all.pdf | archivedate=17 October 2016 | df= }}</ref> There are at least 310 camps in China (''[[China Daily]]'', 2007).<ref name="XH abolition">{{cite web | last=Wu | first=Jiao | work=[[China Daily]] | url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2007-03/01/content_816358.htm | title=New law to abolish laojiao system | date=1 March 2007 | accessdate=18 October 2008}}</ref>
